\begin_body

\begin_layout Description
Example: A car starts from rest acquires a velocity v with uniform acceleration
 
\begin_inset Formula $2ms^{-2}$
\end_inset

 then it comes to stop with uniform retardation 
\begin_inset Formula $4ms^{-2}$
\end_inset

 .
 If the total time for which it remains in motion is 3 sec, the total distance
 travelled is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
a) 2 m
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
b) 3 m
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
c) 4 m
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
d) 6 m 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
{Hint: For solving this problem, we draw the graph of the problem, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename D:/Projects/Images/CC/P-Graphs/4e/Images/KinematicsClassicalApproach/ImagesReduced/Q1-secondequation-Answers.jpg
	scale 56

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Accordning to graph, let the time when it reaches maximum velocity be T,
 and the maximum velocity be V.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

V = 2XT and also V = 4X(3-T)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Equating the equations,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
2T = 12-4T = V
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

6T = 12
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

T = 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 V = 2T = 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Calculating the area under the graph using the calculated parameters, Area
 = 1/2 X 4 X 3 = 6m
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
So , area under the graph is 6m = displacement .
 Also, as all the area is on the positive side, so distance = 6m.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
}
\end_layout

\end_body
